    <prp:abstract>One of the most important questions in the astrophysics of the interstellar medium (ISM) is whether, how, when, and where water and organic molecules are formed and could this have a bearing on the origin of life on Earth? In that connection, water H2O is one of the major key species. Water has been detected widely in the dense ISM, in particular toward the massive star forming region Orion-KL. More specifically, the detection of the isotopologue HD18O in Orion-KL implies that either there is a high D/H ratio molecular clump or there is a very high column of water present. The recent Herschel detection of the isotopologues H218O and H217O suggests that a tiny water factory (&lt;2"), with a column density of about 2e20 cm-2, is the most likely hypothesis. We intend to resolve this water factory by imaging the distribution of the emission of the H2O v2=1 (1(1,0)-1(0,1)) line. Also, this transition being detected in the Orion-KL Herschel observations, we seek to merge the legacy of both Herschel and ALMA.</prp:abstract>
